Macedonians will vote in referendum if they want to change country name
On Sunday, Macedonian citizens voted in a referendum if they wished the country’s name changed to the “Republic of North Macedonia”, a change that would resolve a decade-old dispute with Greece, which opposed its accession to the European Union and NATO.
Greece, which comprises a province called Macedonia, claims that the name of the neighboring country represents a claim on its territory and opposed its accession to the EU and NATO.
The two governments agreed in June on the proposed new name, but opposition nationalists argue that this change would undermine the ethnic identity of Macedonia’s Slavic majority population.
President Gjorge Ivanov said he will not vote in the referendum and that a boycott campaign has raised doubts as to the presence of the vote, and it is possible that the minimum 50% threshold needed to validate the referendum may not be reached.
The question on the ballot paper in the referendum will be: “Do you agree to join the EU and NATO, accepting the agreement with Greece?”
Supporters of the name change, including Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, say it is a price to be paid by Macedonia, one of the countries that resulted from the destruction of Yugoslavia, in order to be accepted in entities such as the EU and NATO.
“I am here today to vote for the future of the country, so that young Macedonians can live freely under the umbrella of the European Union, because this means safer lives for all of us,” said 79-year-old Olivera Georgijevska in Skopje.
Although it is not legally binding, quite a few Members of Parliament said they would respect the outcome of the vote to make it decisive.
In order for the name to be changed, a two-thirds quorum in parliament is required.
The state electoral commission said no irregularities were reported by 13:00.
However, participation was only 16%, compared to 34% in the last parliamentary elections in 2016, when 66% of people with the right to vote submitted.
“I came to vote for my children and for our place in Europe,” said 62-year-old Gjose Tanevski, a voter from Skopje, the country’s capital.
On September 30, 2018, Macedonian Prime Minister Zoran Zaev, his wife, Zorica, and their son, Dusko, voted for a referendum on Macedonia's name change, allowing it to join NATO and enter the European Union.
In front of the Skopje parliament, 54-year-old Vladimir Kavardarkov prepared a small scene and took seats in front of the high-ranking tents of those who would boycott the referendum.
“We support NATO and the EU, but we want to join them with the front up, not the back door,” Kavadarkov said.
“We are a poor country, but we have dignity.
If we are not wanted by the name of Macedonia, we can head to other countries, such as China and Russia, and we can become part of the Eurasian Union.”
Prime Minister Zaev said that joining NATO will bring the investments so necessary to Macedonia, which has a unemployment rate of more than 20%.
“I think the majority will be in favour of changing the name because more than 80 percent of our citizens are in favor of NATO and EU membership,” Zaev said.
He said a result in favor of changing the name would be “confirming our future.”
According to a poll published last Monday by the Institute of Policy Research, between 30% and 43% of citizens with the right to vote will participate in the referendum, below the required number of participants.
According to another survey conducted by Telma TV in Macedonia, 57% of respondents plan to vote on Sunday.
Of those, 70% said they would vote in favor of the change.
For the referendum to be valid, the voting attendance must be 50% plus one vote.
The failure of the referendum would be the first major political blow to the pro-Western government since its takeover in May last year.
