John Edward: Linguistic Skills, Essential for Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sport, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), are striving to provide services at the highest level to their students and parents.
Independent schools offer to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen career, and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desired subject of choice within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will come to his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, the words come to his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year’s competition, we note that foreign languages are among the top rankings, with the highest rates of promotion in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; also 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French and 63% of those who study Spanish have obtained a certificate.
This demonstrates that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, as a subject, hold the same as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that, for reasons employers gave to fight for vacancies, 17% were attributed to a language skills deficit.
Therefore, increasingly, linguistic skills become imperative for preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person ahead of the competition.
According to a survey by YouGov of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to have a conversation, and French was the only two-digit language spoken, 15%.
Therefore, investing in learning foreign languages is important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially in developing economies, children will have more chances of finding meaningful jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other foreign languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn the languages that are considered to be the most important for the UK when looking forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interest, there will always be more languages of choice within independent schools, with faculty who specialize in this field.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future.
It cannot be denied right now, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so it must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done well (it has to be done).
John Edward is Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools
