Harvard Students Take Courses on How to Rest Enough
A new Harvard University course this year encourages students to sleep more, in an attempt to fight the growing “macho” culture that makes them submit to “all night” learning sessions energized with a lot of caffeine.
A scientist has discovered that, often, students of the world’s most prestigious universities don’t even master the basic concepts of the way they should take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the one who created the course, which is believed to be the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to create the course after holding a conference on the impact of lack of sleep on the ability to learn.
“A girl finally came and said to me, ‘Why is this being told to me only now, last year?’
She told me she had never been told about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, introduced to the premiere this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep habits help improve academic and athletic performance, as well as overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s executive director of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students were seriously deprived of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course can involve a number of interactive tasks.
Within a section is presented the image of a home room, and students can click on coffee cups, curtains, sports pants and books to tell them what are the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by sleep deficiency, but also about the importance of a sleep program.
In another section, participants were told how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive pictograms, encourages participants to think about their daily schedule.
“We know we can’t change students’ behavior immediately.
But we believe that they have the right to know, just as anyone has the right to know what the effects of smoking on health are,” Professor Czeisler added.
The culture that makes students proud that they learned all night still exists, he adds, adding that modern technology and the increasing pressure imposed on students have turned sleep deprivation into a growing problem.
Sufficient sleep, of good quality, should be a student’s “secret weapon” to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation makes the brain think that the body is hungry, that you constantly starve, what you’re doing on your chest.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student studying chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler create the course after attending one of his courses in his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course for all students.
The next step, he hopes, is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before enrolling in this institution where the competition is fierce.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students program an alarm to know when it’s time to go to bed, as well as for the hour of waking up, and to know what are the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LEDs, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm when it comes to causing it.
