World Wide Web Inventor Plans to Establish New Internet to Make Competition for Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a startup that wants to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest technology legend project, Inrupt, is a company based on Berners-Lee’s Solid, open-source platform.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is stored and who has the right to access the information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that the intention behind Inrupt was “global domination.”
“Now we have to do it,” he said of the startup.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid technology to allow people to create their own “online personal data archives” or PODs.
It may contain contact lists, programs, calendars, music libraries or other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify would all be available in one browser, all at once.
What is unique about this online personal data archive is that the user has complete control over who can access this type of information.
The company calls this “personal data consolidation”.
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea is that Inrupt contributes with appropriate resources, processes and skills so that Solid is available to everyone.
Currently, the company is composed of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a team of developers working on the project, and a community of volunteer programmers.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized apps using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team did not talk to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a complete change when their business models are completely overhead at once.
“We don’t ask for your permission.”
In a post on Medium, Berners-Lee wrote that “Inrupt’s mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of a new Internet on Solid.”
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate on the neutrality of the Internet.
Even after launching Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m incredibly optimistic for this next era of the Internet,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: the clergyman who won the Victorian Cross in the First World War is celebrated
The only Anglican Church clergyman to win a Victorian Cross medal as a fighter in World War I was celebrated in his hometown after 100 years.
Lieutenant-Colonel Reverend Bernard Vann won the medal on 29 September 1918 in the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was killed by a gunman four days later and never knew that he had been awarded Britain’s highest military honor.
A memorial stone was unveiled on Saturday by his two grandchildren during the parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his nephews, Michael Vann, said he was "symbolically dismayed" that the stone would be unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather won the medal.
According to the London Gazette, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion across the Saint-Quentin Canal "in a very soft fog and under the intense fire of artillery and machine guns."
Later, he hurried to get to the first line and, with a "fantastic bravery", opened the way for the soldiers, then attacked himself a nest of artillery and managed to eliminate three of the detachment weapons.
Lieutenant Colonel Vann was killed by a German gunman on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
The 72-year-old Michael Vann said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I’ll never be able to match, but that makes me feel shy.”
He, along with his brother, Dr. James Vann, also deposited a crown after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Orchestra.
Michael Vann said he "feels very honoured to play a role in the parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is demonstrated by the support that a lot of people give him."
