National Trust spies the secret life of lionesses
New research on a property in the Scottish Highlands wants to reveal how lionesses use their environment to hunt prey.
It is hoped that the findings will reveal new things about the behavior of these unprecedented flying mammals and help future conservation activities.
The study, conducted by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland, will analyze common dwarf dwarfs and pygmy dwarfs, as well as ear dwarfs and water dwarfs from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activity of the lily throughout the season.
The NHS team and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using manual detectors.
A specialized audio analysis of all recordings will estimate the frequency of sounds made by lionesses and what species emit certain sounds.
There will also be produced a habitat map and a report, to create a detailed, scaled image of their behaviour in the environment.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for NTS, hopes that the results will reveal which areas in the habitat are most important for lionesses and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating a lawn, and which is the best way to maintain forest meadows and other associated species.
The populations of lionesses in Scotland and throughout the United Kingdom have declined considerably in the last century.
They are endangered by the construction and development work that affects their nests, as well as the loss of their habitat.
And wind turbines and public lighting are risks, just like mosquito traps and some chemical treatments for building materials, as well as domestic cat attacks.
In fact, lionesses are not blind.
However, because they hunt at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching peaches.
They use a sophisticated ecolocation technique to accurately identify insects and obstacles on their flight path.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major parks and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, is thinking very seriously about lily.
