“Here at Threave, the area is great for lionesses,” he says.
“We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and a perfect habitat.
But there are many things we don’t know about lionesses, so the work we do here and elsewhere will help us understand why they need them to multiply.”
It emphasizes the importance of looking for lionesses before performing maintenance work on the property, as the simple unintentional destruction of a maternal nest could kill up to 400 females and chickens, which can destroy all the local population.
Lilies are protected, and killing, harassing or disturbing them, as well as destroying their nests, are prohibited actions.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish official at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help them.
She said, “We still have a lot to learn about lionesses and we don’t know how populations evolve for many of our species.”
