Foreign buyers will be charged a higher court fee when buying a property in the UK, and additional money will be used to help homeless people, as Theresa May announced today.
The change will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young people with the right to vote, promising more affordable homes and targeting high-income people.
The higher stamp court fee will be applied to natural and legal persons who are not taxpayers in the UK, and the additional money thus obtained will be used to support the government’s efforts to help homeless people.
The surcharge, which adds to the current stamp court fee, including the high levels of the last two years for the second property and the properties purchased for rent, could reach a value of 3%.
The Treasury expects this change to bring an extra of up to 120 million pounds a year.
Approximately 13% of newly built properties in London are purchased by non-residents in the UK, leading to price increases and making it difficult for those who want to buy their first home.
Several prosperous areas of the country, especially in the capital, have become "fantasy cities" due to the high number of foreign buyers spending much of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in the stamp court fee to help young people buy their first home.
He accused the large construction companies of keeping property prices high as a result of the purchase of land without using them, and asked Theresa May to give up the fees for affordable homes in order to solve the UK’s “house-related problem”.
Corbyn announced a number of attractive real estate reform proposals, including leasing controls and halting unmotivated evacuations.
He also wants to give the councils greater powers when it comes to building new homes.
Theresa May said: “Last year I stated that I will dedicate my prime minister’s mandate to fulfilling the British dream of a better life for every new generation.
And that means fixing the problems that exist in the real estate market.
The UK will always be open to people who want to live, work, and build a life here.
However, it is not fair that people who do not live in the UK, as well as companies based abroad, can buy homes as easily as British residents who work hard.
