Here are some key information about Palu and Donggala, from the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the province in the center of Sulawesi Island, located at the end of a narrow bay on the western coast of Sulawesi Island, with a population of about 379,800 in 2017.
The city celebrated its 40th anniversary when it was hit by a tsunami and earthquake.
Donggala is a regency that extends along a coastline with an area of more than 300 km northwest of Sulawesi Island.
Regenza, an administrative region located under a province, has a population of about 299,200 in 2017.
Fisheries and agriculture activities are the central point of the province's economy in the center of Sulawesi Island, in particular the Donggala coastal region.
Mining activities for nickel extraction are also important in the province, but are concentrated mainly in Morowali, on the opposite coast of Sulawesi Island.
Palu and Donggala have been hit by tsunamis several times in the past 100 years, according to Indonesia’s Disaster Management Agency.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
Also in 1996, a tsunami struck the western part of the Donggala Regency, killing nine people.
Indonesia is located in the Pacific Fire Circle, an area with intense seismic activity.
Here are some of the earthquakes and tsunamis that have occurred in recent years:
2004: On December 26, a powerful earthquake on the western coast of Indonesian province Aceh, north of Sumatra, triggered a tsunami that struck 14 countries, killing 226,000 people on the Indian Ocean coast, more than half of them in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra Island in late March and early April.
Hundreds of people died on the island of Nias, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-degree magnitude earthquake on the Richter scale struck the south of Indonesia's most populous islands, Java, triggering a tsunami that struck the south coast, killing nearly 700 people.
